Live proof — background embedding indexer + nomic-embed-text quality
=====================================================================

Machine: this box embeds ~0.5s per real 1024-char code chunk via local Ollama
(measured: 30.5s for a batch of 64). A full 2137-symbol index is minutes of
work, so it MUST run off the search path and survive restarts.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
(b) BACKGROUND INDEXER — fills the index behind BM25, checkpointed
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Started `pirs --mode repl --semantic --embed-model nomic-embed-text
--embed-max-chars 512` and left it idle. code_search is query-only (embed_cap
= 0); a background task fills the embedding index in batches of 64, persisting
each batch before the next. The repl stayed fully responsive throughout.

Observed embedding count climbing while the process idled (nothing blocked):
  t+25s   64
  t+50s   320
  t+75s   448
  t+100s  576
  t+125s  768
  ...     1024, 1152, 1280, 1472, 1536, 1728, 1920
  ~7 min  2137  (FULL — every code symbol embedded)

Killed the host; the 2137 vectors persisted in .pirs/graph.db (survives
restart). Resumability + no-rework-on-restart are test-pinned:
  crates/pirs-graph/tests/bg_index_test.rs
    - fills_whole_index_behind_the_search_path (each symbol embedded once)
    - resumes_after_kill_without_reembedding   (run 2 embeds ONLY the remainder)

This is the fix for the old inline path, which stored only at the very end:
a kill at 7.5 min there persisted ZERO vectors. Here, a kill loses at most the
one in-flight batch.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
(a) NOMIC-EMBED-TEXT QUALITY — honest comparison vs all-minilm
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Same two queries as the all-minilm runs. Results are FUSED
[lexical+semantic+graph], so BM25 contributes to both.

Q1 "decide whether a source file has changed and needs re-parsing ... staleness":
  1. load_source (crates/pirs-rhai/src/lib.rs:447)  [30 callers]
  2. incremental_refresh_equals_full_parse_across_add_change_delete (store_test.rs:54)
  3. first_changed_line (crates/pirs-tools/src/edit.rs:281)
  4. on_tool_result_records_only_source_files (mutation_guard_test.rs:81)
  5. refresh (crates/pirs-graph/src/store.rs:108)  [5 callers]   <- the real answer, #5

Q2 "change what an already-running agent turn is doing without stopping it":
  1. run_turn (crates/pirs/src/main.rs:1203)
  2. run_agent_loop (crates/pirs-agent/src/agent_loop.rs:66)
  3. run_strategy_turn (crates/pirs/src/main.rs:1281)
  4. on_should_stop_ends_loop_after_turn (loop_hooks_test.rs:131)
  5. turn_end_event_carries_usage (packs2_test.rs:266)
  -> NONE are the steering mechanism (steer / job_steer / agent.steer). It
     clustered on "run turn / loop" and missed the actual concept.

VERDICT: nomic-embed-text is NOT meaningfully better than all-minilm here.
  - Q1: comparable — the real function `refresh` shows at #5, the incremental
    test at #2, but much of that is BM25 matching "re-parsing"/"incremental",
    not the embedding.
  - Q2: still weak — neither general model maps "change a running turn" to the
    domain term "steer".
Both are GENERAL text models despite the name; the quality lever is a
CODE-SPECIFIC embedder (nomic-embed-code, jina-code, voyage-code-3), not a
bigger general model. The infrastructure (background index, service client)
is now ready to consume one; the model is a config choice via --embed-model.

